node.text: Cynthia DiBartolo’s journey to the New York Stock Exchange floor was fraught with challenges and difficulty. In July 2021, DiBartolo’s firm, Tigress Financial Partners, became the first disabled and woman-owned floor broker to become a member of the NYSE. Prior to launching Tigress Financial in 2011, DiBartolo served as a compliance director, an attorney, and as a risk management director for some of Wall Streets’ largest firms. However, her life would change in 2009 with a diagnosis of throat and neck cancer. DiBartolo became severely disabled following life-saving surgery that compromised her ability to eat, speak and swallow. But inspiration from her father convinced her that she needed to act; “They took your tongue, not your brain.” her father told her. Using her experience from decades on Wall Street and tenacity DiBartolo launched the first and nation’s only disabled and woman-owned financial services firm.

node.title: The 1st disabled and woman-owned NYSE floor broker is changing Wall Street

node.text: Being a millionaire may be more common than you think. About 20 million people in the U.S. have enough assets to fit the definition, according to a 2020 study by Credit Suisse. Chris Hogan, author of the book “Everyday Millionaires,” surveyed more than 10,000 of those wealthy individuals to figure out their secret to success. Having a particular mindset almost universally contributed to millionaires’ success, Hogan said. He found that around 97% of millionaires surveyed believed they were in control of their own destiny. That is much higher than the 55% of the general population Hogan found to hold the same opinion. Check out this video to see the other four beliefs and practices that more than 90% of millionaires apply to their money.

node.title: More than 90% of millionaires used these five tools to build wealth

node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

The Covid-19 pandemic has radically shifted the work landscape, as millions of Americans switched career paths or said goodbye to the office forever.⁠
⁠
While U.S. employment will experience stunted growth over the next 10 years, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reports, certain jobs will be soaring in demand.⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'How a 26-year-old paid off $23,000 in debt and grew her net worth to $100,000 in 2 years CNBC'.

node.text:
In 2018, Cinneah El-Amin noticed a disconnect on her social media feeds: personal finance and travel felt mutually exclusive. ⁠
⁠
With that, her travel- and personal finance-focused lifestyle blog, Flynanced, was born. Though El-Amin didn’t start sharing her personal finance journey publicly until 2020, by that time she was already on the path to achieving two big financial goals: paying off $23,000 in credit card and student loan debt, and growing her net worth to $100,000. She reached both of those milestones within two years.⁠
⁠
Red how the 26-year-old made it happen at the link in bio. (In partnership with @acorns #investinyou)

node.text:
Climate change is getting personal.⁠
⁠
Four in five people are willing to make changes to how they work and live to help reduce the effects of global climate change, according to new data released Tuesday by the nonpartisan Pew Research Center. Only 19% of those surveyed reported they would be willing to make only a few or no changes at all to help reduce the effects of global climate change.⁠
⁠
But there's a party-line split in the U.S. Find out the percentage of American conservatives who said they were willing to change how they live and work to help reduce the effects of global climate change at the link in bio.

node.text:
Every second counts to make a strong first impression during a job interview.⁠
⁠
One particular slip-up, however, could knock you out of the running for your dream job — and it’s a mistake that, surprisingly, a lot of candidates make, Amazon senior recruiter DJ Cabeen tells @CNBCMakeIt. “My biggest pet peeve is when candidates use curse words or inappropriate language during an interview,” he says. “It’s a major turnoff, it does not go over well or feel professional at all.”⁠
⁠
What's another common gaffe Cabeen has noticed during interviews? Link in bio.

node.text:
Unhappiness can be expensive. 💰⁠
⁠
According to a report, 85% of employees are not engaged at work, and it's costing our economy approximately $7 trillion in lost productivity each year.⁠ While it's important for business leaders to take action, employees are also encouraged to seek out their own ways of boosting satisfaction at work. Why? A cheery disposition — and not a bigger paycheck — can actually make you better at your job and less likely to quit.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in bio for research-backed happiness hacks might just tick up your level of on-the-job satisfaction. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
Gymshark founder Ben Francis says he doesn’t view big-name sportswear brands as a threat to his relatively young $1 billion label. ⁠
⁠
Rather, he argued that many of those businesses were actually trying to pivot toward a business model similar to that of Gymshark. ⁠
⁠
Gymshark sells its fitnesswear exclusively online and only through its own website. The brand was an early adopter of influencer marketing, partnering with well-known fitness YouTubers and building a community of its own ambassadors, known as “Gymshark athletes.” ⁠
⁠
Why is Francis not too concerned with incumbent brands trying to do the same? Link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
One of our children’s deepest needs is to feel heard, and by listening carefully and expressing empathy, parents can help fill this need.⁠
⁠
More importantly, research has found that if someone feels empathy, even if it’s just from watching a touching video, it can make them feel more connected to — and generous toward — others. In other words, practicing empathy with your kids can help them grow up to be emotionally intelligent adults.⁠
⁠
This might not seem hard, but it is. To read about some of the most effective ways to teach children empathy, visit the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

From investing icon Warren Buffett to Hollywood superstar Daniel Craig, celebrities have been making headlines in recent months by revealing that they don’t intend to leave their massive fortunes to their children.⁠
⁠
Kevin O’Leary, O’Shares ETFs chairman, shares a similar distaste for inheritances. In fact, O’Leary doesn’t plan to leave any inheritance to his children, he tells @CNBCMakeIt. Instead, he used his wealth to create a trust to take care of his family — but only to a certain point.⁠
⁠
Details on why he says that he chose to do this out of a desire to not “curse” his children at the link in bio.

node.text:
Inspiration4, which launched with Elon Musk's SpaceX on Wednesday evening, shared the first photos from day one in orbit and gave an up-close look at the expansive views of Earth from the spacecraft's "cupola" window.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The crew spent its first day in orbit floating in zero gravity inside the capsule. The historic private mission — which includes commander Jared Isaacman, pilot Sian Proctor, medical officer Hayley Arceneaux and mission specialist Chris Sembroski — is orbiting the planet at an altitude of 585 kilometers (363.5 miles), which is above the International Space Station and the highest altitude humans have traveled in years.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
